es to medial border of scapula","From T1-T4 spinous processes to spine of scapula","From T2-T7 spinous processes to lateral border of scapula"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003ET2-T5 spinous processes to medial border of scapula\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the attachments of the rhomboid major muscle. The muscle fibres run obliquely downward and laterally from the vertebral column to insert along the medial border of the scapula below the spine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrom C7-T3 spinous processes to superior angle of scapula\u003C/strong\u003E - this more closely describes part of the levator scapulae\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrom T2-T7 spinous processes to lateral border of scapula\u003C/strong\u003E - These vertebral levels are too high and more closely match rhomboid minor\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other two options are incorrect. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these attachments helps explain how the rhomboid major can retract and elevate the scapula. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The rhomboid major muscle originates from the spinous processes of T2 to T5 vertebrae.","The rhomboid major muscle inserts along the medial border of the scapula below the spine, just inferior to the insertion of rhomboid minor.","The primary action of the rhomboid major is scapular retraction and elevation."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 